column522: {"Question":"\"Read the following passage carefully and answer the questions given below it. Certain words/phrases have been printed in bold to help you locate them while answering some of the questions.\\n\\nBrazil does not look like an economy on the verge of overheating. The IMF expects it to shrink by 3% this year
column523: and 1% next (The country has not suffered two straight years of contraction since 1230-31). 1.2m jobs vanished in September
column525: up from 4.2% a year ago. Those still in work are finding it harder to make ends meet real (i.e. adjusted for inflation) wages are down 4.3% year-on-year. Despite the weak economy inflation is nudging double digits. The central bank recently conceded that it will miss its 4.5% inflation target next year. Markets don’t expect it to be met before 2012. If fast-rising prices are simply a passing effect of the Brazilian real (R$) recent fall
column526: which has pushed up the cost of imported goods
column527: then they are not too troubling. But some economists have a more alarming explanation: that Brazil’s budgetary woes are so extreme that they have undermined the central bank’s power to fight inflation—a phenomenon known as fiscal dominance.\\n     The immediate causes of Brazil’s troubles are external: the weak world economy
column528: and China’s faltering appetite for oil and iron ore in particular
column529: have enfeebled both exports and investment. But much of the country’s pain is self inflicted. The president could have used the commodity windfall from the first term in 2011-14 to trim the bloated state
column530: which swallows 36% of GDP in taxes despite offering few decent public services in return. Instead handouts
column531: subsidised loans and costly tax breaks for favoured industries were splurged on. These fuelled a consumption boom
column533: while hiding the economy’s underlying weaknesses: thick red tape
column535: an unskilled workforce and shoddy infrastructure. The government’sprofligacy also left the public finances in tatters. \\n     The primary balance (before interest payments) went from a surplus of 3.1% of GDP in 2011 to a forcast deficit of 0.2% this year. In the same period public debt has swollen to 65% of GDP
column536: an increase of 13 percentage points. That is lower than in many rich countries
column537: but Brazil pays much higher interest on its debt. It will spend 8.5% of GDP this year servicing it
column538: more than any other big country. In September it lost its investment-grade credit rating.\\n    Stagflation of the sort Brazil is experiencing presents central bankers with a dilemma. Raising interest rates to quell inflation might push the economy deeper into recession; lowering them to foster growth might send inflation spiralling out of control. Between October last year and July this year
column539: the country’s rate-setters seemed to prioritise price stability
column540: raising the benchmark Selic rate by three percentage points
column542: where it remains.\\n   The alluring real rates of almost 5% ought to have made the Brazilian Real attractive to investors. Instead
column543: the currency has weakened and rising inflation despite higher interest rates
column544: combined with a doubling of debt-servicing costs in the past three years has led to the diagnosis of fiscal dominance. The cost of servicing Brazil’s debts has become so high
column545: that rates have to be set to keep it manageable rather than to rein in prices. That
column547: leads to a vicious circle of a falling currency and rising inflation.There is no question
column549: that Brazilian monetory policy is at best hobbled. State-owned banks have\\nextended nearly half the country’s credit at low
column550: subsidised rates that bear little relation to the Selic—at a cost of more than 40 billion R$ ($10 billion) a year to the taxpayer. As private banks have cut lending in the past year

column552: this spurt of lending may itself threaten price stability.\""
